                        h2 Why is the point of sales (POS) system important?
                        p.lead
                            | A Point of Sale (POS) system is a transaction processing device used mostly by retail customers. The system comprises both hardware and software designed to facilitate payment acceptance and in-person sales for your business. Additionally, it efficiently transfers funds to your bank account following each transaction.
                        p.lead
                            | It is a physical computing device often found in a physical store or a checkout point in an online store. The software accompanying POS devices is a sophisticated system constituting features that enable retailers, suppliers, and distributors (wholesalers) to monitor inventory and purchasing patterns, ensure accurate pricing, and gather valuable marketing data.
                        p.lead
                            | Usually, a point-of-sale system refers to the cash register in physical stores. Today, modern POS systems are fully digital, enabling you to process customer transactions from any location. All that's required is a POS software and a computing device, such as a tablet or desktop.

